271
00:18:40,160 --> 00:18:42,159
The point is to use water that is only as hot as the water

272
00:18:42,160 --> 00:18:43,959
you take a bath in.

273
00:18:43,960 --> 00:18:47,659
Moreover, by doing this, the lettuce stays crisp for a while

274
00:18:47,660 --> 00:18:50,559
even after you put it in the sandwich.

275
00:18:50,560 --> 00:18:54,859
Amuro, who on earth are you?

276
00:18:54,860 --> 00:18:57,159
Oh, and though the bread is the main material,

277
00:18:57,160 --> 00:18:59,359
"Price cut" -this type of bread will do.

278
00:18:59,360 --> 00:19:00,360
What?

279
00:19:00,560 --> 00:19:02,159
That's the kind you were using?

280
00:19:02,160 --> 00:19:04,859
This way, I can get it at half price.

281
00:19:04,860 --> 00:19:07,659
I guess so, but...

282
00:19:07,660 --> 00:19:09,159
But, the taste...

283
00:19:09,160 --> 00:19:12,959
Rather, bread that's a bit hard is better.

284
00:19:12,960 --> 00:19:14,659
What? Why?

285
00:19:14,660 --> 00:19:16,459
The secret is this.

286
00:19:16,460 --> 00:19:18,160
A steamer?

287
00:19:21,860 --> 00:19:24,160
Please try touching the bread that is inside.

288
00:19:27,260 --> 00:19:29,659
Fantastic! It's soft and fluffy!

289
00:19:29,660 --> 00:19:32,959
Just before making the sandwich, you steam it a bit.

290
00:19:32,960 --> 00:19:36,859
That way, the bread absorbs as much moisture as it has hardened.

291
00:19:36,860 --> 00:19:37,959
I see.

292
00:19:37,960 --> 00:19:41,159
That's why the bread was warm even though it wasn't toasted.

293
00:19:41,160 --> 00:19:44,559
Moreover, you can keep the price down.

294
00:19:44,560 --> 00:19:46,859
Amuro, you were taking your job

295
00:19:46,860 --> 00:19:49,260
at this coffee shop seriously too, weren't you?

296
00:19:51,060 --> 00:19:53,760
Miso mayonnaise sauce, eh.

297
00:19:55,760 --> 00:19:58,359
But the soft fluffiness you get by doing all this

298
00:19:58,360 --> 00:20:00,659
doesn't keep for long.

299
00:20:00,660 --> 00:20:03,059
That's why it's good to eat at the shop,

300
00:20:03,060 --> 00:20:06,059
but not good for take-out.

301
00:20:06,060 --> 00:20:08,059
I'm a baker.

302
00:20:08,060 --> 00:20:10,959
I can improvise with bread.

303
00:20:10,960 --> 00:20:15,659
Please let me sell your sandwich at my shop!

304
00:20:15,660 --> 00:20:17,159
What?

305
00:20:17,160 --> 00:20:20,359
But, sir... I don't think...

306
00:20:20,360 --> 00:20:21,559
Okay.

307
00:20:21,560 --> 00:20:23,960
You mean... it's okay?

308
00:20:24,660 --> 00:20:27,559
You fell in love with my ham sandwich.

309
00:20:27,560 --> 00:20:30,160
I'd really like someone like you to sell my sandwiches.

310
00:20:32,160 --> 00:20:36,860
"Poirot"

311
00:22:04,860 --> 00:22:07,059
They're ready. Please try them.

312
00:22:07,060 --> 00:22:09,160
Dig in.

313
00:22:09,860 --> 00:22:12,359
-Delicious! -Super soft and fluffy!

314
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:14,459
This sauce is good.

315
00:22:14,460 --> 00:22:18,659
True. The bread is warm and the contents aren't cold either.

316
00:22:18,660 --> 00:22:20,860
This is it! This taste!

317
00:22:22,160 --> 00:22:25,059
If the customers want to eat it at the shop, they can do so at Poirot

318
00:22:25,060 --> 00:22:28,359
and if they want to take it home, they can buy it at your bakery.

319
00:22:28,360 --> 00:22:31,359
I think it's a great idea.

320
00:22:31,360 --> 00:22:32,959
Thank you very much!

321
00:22:32,960 --> 00:22:35,659
I'll develop bread that can keep soft a fluffy for a long time

322
00:22:35,660 --> 00:22:38,159
and keep the taste of the sandwich as close to yours as possible,

323
00:22:38,160 --> 00:22:41,359
so as to keep up the good reputation that Poirot has made for itself.

324
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:43,759
Yes. Please do that.

325
00:22:43,760 --> 00:22:45,259
Well...

326
00:22:45,260 --> 00:22:47,259
If you're going to use the name Poirot,

327
00:22:47,260 --> 00:22:50,060
I think we should get permission from the store manager first.

328
00:22:51,160 --> 00:22:53,659
Oh, please excuse me.

329
00:22:53,660 --> 00:22:55,359
Yes, Amuro here.

330
00:22:55,360 --> 00:22:57,060
Hi, Bourbon.

331
00:22:59,860 --> 00:23:01,360
Vermouth.

332
00:23:02,460 --> 00:23:06,759
It seems that you've recently been secretly checking.

333
00:23:06,760 --> 00:23:09,760
Checking? What?

334
00:23:14,160 --> 00:23:18,159
If I knew what, I wouldn't be calling you like this.

335
00:23:18,160 --> 00:23:19,959
I guess not.

336
00:23:19,960 --> 00:23:22,659
Well, you'd better watch yourself.

337
00:23:22,660 --> 00:23:25,759
It seems that they're keeping a close watch over you recently.

338
00:23:25,760 --> 00:23:28,159
Keeping close watch over me...

339
00:23:28,160 --> 00:23:29,160
Who is?

340
00:23:30,460 --> 00:23:31,660
Gin.

341
00:23:43,960 --> 00:23:45,959
What're you looking at?

342
00:23:45,960 --> 00:23:48,759
Kyona Shono's blog.

343
00:23:48,760 --> 00:23:51,159
Come to think of it, she was saying that

344
00:23:51,160 --> 00:23:55,259
the secret of Saya Kitami was written on her blog or whatnots.

345
00:23:55,260 --> 00:23:56,559
Yeah...

346
00:23:56,560 --> 00:23:58,459
Please open the door!

347
00:23:58,460 --> 00:24:00,160
Yes, but...

348
00:24:02,360 --> 00:24:03,560
Kyona?

349
00:24:08,160 --> 00:24:09,659
Next Conan,

350
00:24:09,660 --> 00:24:13,660
"The Actress Blogger's Locked Room Case (Part 1)"

